            <p>
                Hey, I'm Max.
            </p>
            <p>
                I've always been fascinated by how people think, decide, and interact. Human minds are incredibly complex and unique, and yet often surprisingly predictable.
            </p>
            <p>
                Besides human psychology, I often read/listen/discuss about health(span), science and ancient wisdom.
            </p>
            <p>
                When I come across a concept that I really want to remember, I like to turn it into a drawing. <br />
                It helps me recall it instantly. No need to dig through the back of my mind, just a quick glance at the visual and it’s there.
                Happy to share some of these (visual) learnings here with you. Hopefully they spark something for you too :) 
            </p>            
            <p>
                Since 2011, I've been channeling my curiosity into helping companies grow. I've worked with businesses from 0 to €100M ARR across ecommerce, SaaS, consumer products, and web3. <br />
                Whatever the context, I start by understanding people. They're the heartbeat of every business.
            </p>            
            <p>
                From there, I design systems that make growth sustainable. <br />
                I most often work at the intersection of product and marketing (aka growth marketing). I enjoy having a holistic view and impact on the whole journey; not just the top of the funnel.
                Sometimes that means building acquisition and retention loops. <br />
                Sometimes it's defining the right metrics, crafting creative campaigns, aligning product and marketing, or applying behavioral science to improve conversion.
            </p>
            
            <p>
                If there's one thing I've learned, it's this: tools change fast, but people's underlying drivers don't.<br />
                That's why I keep coming back to psychology and basic principles: understand the pain, build trust, tell the right story at the right time, the rest usually follows.
            </p>
            
            <p>
